The membrane usually separates two fluids (aqueous phases) of much smaller viscosity. In the first instance, we can therefore neglect the tangential stresses on the surfaces ofthe sheet, which models the membrane. The motion in the sheet is then two-dimensional, with no variation of flow properties across the sheet. Thus the drag and torque are those on a length h of a cylinder moving through a viscous fluid.
